observations.recommendation:
We recommended and re-iterated paraphrased prior year’s audit recommendation that Management require:

All concerned officials and employees to strictly enforce payment of current and past due rentals totaling at least to ₱17.54 million and fully impose the provisions of the City Ordinance and the Contract of Lease particularly when there is breach of contract;

The Market Committee to formulate or develop effective and practical strategies that could enhance collections of all unpaid accounts and effect imposition of penalties/surcharges to defaulting lessees as provided under the terms and conditions of the lease contract to compel prompt rental payment;

The City Treasurer to maintain a complete and updated individual subsidiary ledgers of all stallholders in coordination with the Market Administrator/ OIC-Economic Enterprise Management Unit and other offices responsible over the grant/award of stalls to new stallholders. Henceforth, submit the complete and updated schedule/report of all accounts with the City Accounting Office for recording; and

The Market Committee to formulate plans and adopt strategies/measures to maximize utilization of the spaces or stalls with the end view of generating additional income.

We recommended that Management:
Evaluate and plan thoroughly the proposed priority development projects to be included in the current slice of LDIP, that is the AIP, as to its feasibility and readiness for procurement and implementation during the year;
Reinforce the monitoring and evaluation of implementation of projects and facilitate the prompt completion of detailed engineering activities to avoid delays in the procurement for infrastructure projects;
Revisit the status of unimplemented projects, especially those marked as pending and financial assistance to be given to the barangays, and identify which projects are still implementable within the three-year time frame of LDIP. Update the list of prioritized programs in the LDIP and re-appropriate the funds to other priority development projects that are procurement and implementation ready; and
Monitor the implementation of projects by the barangays and follow up the liquidation of previous financial assistance.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive instruct the City Accountant to:

Prepare adjusting entries for the paid obligations still included in the Accounts Payables and double recording of payables;

Ensure that the JEV for the set-up of accounts payable is properly supported with documents such as Purchase Request, Purchase Order, Sales Invoice/Delivery Receipt and Acceptance and Inspection Report (AIR);

Review thoroughly the long-outstanding payables and prepare appropriate adjusting entries for the reversion to surplus and/or to re-establish the valid clams. In case of trust fund, determine whether the project has been completed and coordinate with the source agencies for the appropriate disposition of the remaining funds;

Revisit their existing disbursement procedures and design a monitoring mechanism to settle its liabilities promptly and avoid the accumulation of long-outstanding and undocumented payables; and

Revisit the existing policy on the retention of money as Warranty Security against defects on the procured expendable and non-expendable items.

We reiterated our prior year’s recommendation that Management:

Plan thoroughly the budget for the 20 per cent DF and pursue improved practices in programming, prioritizing and implementing programs and projects to maximize the implementation of development projects to ensure that optimum benefits are derived by the greater number of its constituents;

Meticulously and judiciously review and evaluate projects before its inclusion in the Local Development Fund and Annual Investment Plan and provide realistic timelines for its completion;

Observe proper timing in the implementation of the infrastructure projects to give ample time for the implementing office in the prompt accomplishment of the projects; and

Evaluate/assess together with the City Development Council the identified development projects from prior years under the Continuing Appropriations, specifically the Environmental Projects if still feasible, otherwise, re-appropriate/re-align the same for other development projects.

We reiterated our prior year’s recommendations that the Local Chief Executive direct the:

City Accountant to continue with the proper withholding of premiums and loan amortization from employees’ salary;

Acting City Treasurer to remit the full amount that was withheld from employees’ salary, together with the government’s share in the employees’ premiums;

Designated Authorized Officer to submit to GSIS the names of the new employee/s and any change in the employment status of the employees using the Agency Remittance Advice (ARA), the basis for updating the membership profile to reflect the new salary rate, employment status, position, and any other important information.

